**Title**: Quantifying Resolution-Dependent Force Softening and IC-Induced Bias in GPU-Accelerated PM Simulations

**Description**: This research characterizes the interplay between Lagrangian Perturbation Theory (LPT) errors and PM-mesh discretization by systematically comparing $512^3$ and $1024^3$ mesh resolutions within a $1000$ Mpc/h box. By isolating the $k$-range where the PM force-softening scale dominates the power spectrum suppression, we establish a formal validity threshold for the Warp-based simulation framework against the Quijote fiducial. We will quantify the specific $k$-space deviation ($P_{warp}/P_{Quijote}$) across $z \in \{0, 0.5, 1, 2\}$, mapping the transition from IC-dominated ZA inaccuracies to grid-dominated discretization errors. This analysis will produce a transfer function that corrects for PM-softening, providing a high-fidelity calibration for downstream emulator training. The results will establish the precise operational limits of the NVIDIA Warp implementation, enabling users to distinguish physical signal from numerical artifacts at the Nyquist limit.
\end{IDEA}


